 for purposes of amusement and instruction. The book highlights an active and shifting market in history for children, and reveals how children were actively involved in consuming and repackaging the past: from playing with historically themed toys and games to performing in plays and pageants. Each chapter reconstructs encounters across different media, uncovering the cultural work done by particular pasts and exposing the key role of playfulness in the British historical imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren's literature, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aHistory in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aChildren’s culture.  aChildren’s literature.  aClassical reception.  aEighteenth-century.  aHistorical education.  aMedievalism.  aNineteenth-century.  aPlay.  aTwentieth-century.  aUses of the past.1 aBasdeo, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant Davies, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Rachel Bryant, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrenby, M. O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGribling, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGribling, Barbara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeene, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovatt, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Ellie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZimmerman, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruy